               <p>ARN ELWIN. I am the wife of John Elwin - he lives <placeName id="t18310407-257-crimeloc1376">in Wellington-street, Bethnal-green</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18310407-257-crimeloc1376" type="placeName" value="in Wellington-street, Bethnal-green"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18310407-257-crimeloc1376" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310407-257-off1374 t18310407-257-crimeloc1376"></join>, and is a <rs id="t18310407-257-viclabel1377" type="occupation">baker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310407-257-victim1788 t18310407-257-viclabel1377"></join>, On the 25th of February I was in a little room which joins the shop - there is a glass window between them; I saw the prisoner, who had just taken two loaves from the window, and was walking out with them - I opened the door, and called to him; he put them on the threshold, and ran away - I am quite sure he is the person; Mr Gardiner brought him back - put the same loaves on the counter, and the policeman took them.</p>
               <p>EDMUND GARDINER. I live in Wellington-street, Bethnal-green. On the 25th of February I was in Selby-street - the prosecutor's shop is at the corner; I saw the prisoner running fast from their door - the prosecutrix came to the shop, and called to me to stop him, which I did.</p>
               <p>MICHAEL JOURDAN. I am a Police-constable. I was sent for, and took the prisoner - I received two loaves from the prosecutrix and her husband.</p>
               <p>Jury to ANN ELWIN. Q. Was the prisoner in the habit of coming to the shop? A. No - I thought I had seen him pass the door.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 17.</p>
               <p>Recommended to mercy by the Jury.</p>
